Rules:
- Return patches for every user answer you can map to an allowed patch type.
- Use exact step names from the base YAML.
- Do not invent patch types or fields outside the lists below.
- Prefer set_mapping_value for ServiceNow ticket fields on the four ServiceNow Incident steps only.
- Never use set_mapping_value on Find a LM-DX reference steps. Those steps must keep mappings null.
- Never invent mapping field names such as dummy_field or skip.
- Prefer set_delay_seconds for delay steps.
- Prefer set_step_precondition for auto-close rules.
- For Create ServiceNow Incident steps, prefer add_step_precondition_conditions to add severity/state checks while keeping the existing lastOutcome guard. If you use set_step_precondition, include actionsystem.action.lastOutcome in the conditions list.
- Use add_step_precondition_conditions only when the user explicitly asks to keep the existing start condition and add more checks.
- If an answer does not map to any allowed patch, skip it.

Map user answers to patches:
- Keys ending in __create_conditions or __alert_create_rules -> add_step_precondition_conditions on Create ServiceNow Incident steps in that group for severity/state checks. Do not remove the existing lastOutcome guard.
- Create ServiceNow Incident for this alert must keep lastOutcome = Alert updated.
- Create ServiceNow Incident for this insight must keep lastOutcome = Insight updated.
- Keys ending in __create_mappings, __update_mappings, or __insight_update_mappings -> set_mapping_value on ServiceNow steps in that group
- Keys ending in __correlation_delay or __delay_durations -> set_delay_seconds on Delay steps in that group
- Keys ending in __auto_close_rules -> set_step_precondition on Auto-close alerts that are not valid for ticketing and created more than 1 hour ago only
- Keys ending in __sdt_handling, __ai_summarise, or legacy step_removal / sdt_handling / ai_processing_policy -> remove_step only when the user explicitly asks to remove or disable specific steps
- Legacy flat keys still supported: incident_policy, servicenow_mapped_fields, delay_durations, auto_close_policy, assignment_group
- group metadata -> set_group_name or set_group_description

Remove step rules:
- Use remove_step only when the user clearly says a step should be removed, disabled, or not used.
- Do not remove core alert processing steps unless the user explicitly asks.
- Each remove_step patch removes the first step with that exact step_name. Use two patches if the same name appears twice.
- Put remove_step patches before patches that edit remaining steps.
- Safe examples to remove only when the user asks to drop SDT, old AI summarise, or v2-only auto-close paths:
  - Wait for SDT to end whilst continuing to deduplicate further events
  - Flip to new after SDT ends if alert has not been cleared
  - Summarise insights with AI
  - Update Insight with AI Title, Summary and RCA
  - Delay for 24 hours for auto close Alert
  - Auto-close all the alerts
- Never use remove_step to add new steps. remove_step only deletes existing steps.

Incident creation field paths:
- Alert create step: alerts.alertDetails.currentSeverity, alerts.alertDetails.workflowState
- Insight create step: insights.ml.highestSeverity, insights.insightDetails.workflowState
- Do not use insights.severity or insights.state. They are not valid field paths in this base YAML.

Auto-close rules:
- Use set_step_precondition to replace the full start condition. Do not use add_step_precondition_conditions for auto-close.
- Patch only Auto-close alerts that are not valid for ticketing and created more than 1 hour ago.
- Do not patch Auto-close all the alerts unless the user explicitly asks about high-severity 24-hour auto-close.
- Include low-severity checks with alerts.alertDetails.worstSeverity and alerts.alertDetails.currentSeverity when the user mentions low severity.

ServiceNow mapping rules:
- Only patch these steps with set_mapping_value:
  - Create ServiceNow Incident for this alert
  - Create ServiceNow Incident for this insight
  - Update ServiceNow Incident linked to this alert
  - Update ServiceNow Incident linked to this insight
- Do not patch Find a LM-DX reference for this alert or Find a LM-DX reference for this insight.
- Allowed mapping targets: caller_id, resolved_by, assignment_group, state, priority, close_code, close_notes, short_description, work_notes, impact, urgency, category, subcategory, cmdb_ci, contact_type, description.
- If an answer does not map to one of those fields on one of those steps, skip it.
- Use resolved_by only on the two Update ServiceNow Incident steps, not on Create steps.
- caller_id and assignment_group belong on Create steps. Update steps too when the user asks for assignment_group.

Auto-close timing rules:
- For alerts.meta.firstEventTimestamp age checks, use operator OLDER_THAN with value_type hour, minute, or second.
- Example: "older than 1 hour" -> field alerts.meta.firstEventTimestamp, operator OLDER_THAN, value 1, value_type hour
- Also use actionsystem.action.lastOutcome = Delay Completed when the user mentions waiting for a delay to finish.

Common step names in this base YAML:
- Delay for 15 mins to allow new alerts to correlate
- Delay for 1 hour
- Delay for 24 hours for auto close Alert
- Create ServiceNow Incident for this alert
- Create ServiceNow Incident for this insight
- Update ServiceNow Incident linked to this alert
- Update ServiceNow Incident linked to this insight
- Update alert Escalation
- Auto-close alerts that are not valid for ticketing and created more than 1 hour ago
- Auto-close all the alerts

Important:
- ServiceNow fields such as caller_id, resolved_by, assignment_group, state, priority, close_code, close_notes, short_description, and work_notes are mapped fields. Use set_mapping_value for them.
- Runtime behavior settings such as delayTime, additionalInsights, and strictOrder are actionConfig values. Use set_action_config_value for them.
- Auto-close rules are step start conditions. Use set_step_precondition to replace them.
- Incident creation severity/state rules are extra start checks. Use add_step_precondition_conditions on Create ServiceNow Incident steps so the existing lastOutcome guard stays in place.

